glish: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Bayley was born in 1270, in Lancashire, England as the daughter of Bayley. She had at least 1 son with Baron Thurston Jordan De Bayley. She died in 1303, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"Surnud","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1389","1320":"1320","1287":"1287","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"Kuollut","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1389","1320":"1320","1287":"1287","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"Décédé","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1389","1320":"1320","1287":"1287","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Bayley est née en 1270, à Lancashire, Angleterre, fille de Bayley. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Baron Thurston Jordan De Bayley. Elle est décédée en 1303, à l’âge de 33 ans."},"de":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"Verstorben","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1389","1320":"1320","1287":"1287","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Baroness Margaret Bayley wurde 1270 in Lancashire, England, als Tochter von Bayley geboren. Sie hatte mit Baron Thurston Jordan De Bayley mindestens 1 Sohn. Sie starb 1303 im Alter von 33 Jahren."},"ht":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"Desede","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1389","1320":"1320","1287":"1287","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"hu":{"1270–1303":"1270–1303","1287–1338":"1287–1338","1320–1389":"1320–1389","–Male":"elhunyt","1338":"1338","1303":"1303","1389":"1